paragraphs.title: Load the diabetes dataset using scikit-learn
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

# Load the diabetes dataset
diabetes = datasets.load_diabetes()
# Use only one feature
diabetes_X = diabetes.data[:, np.newaxis, 2]
# Split the data into training/testing sets
diabetes_X_train = diabetes_X[:-20]
diabetes_X_test = diabetes_X[-20:]
# Split the targets into training/testing sets
diabetes_y_train = diabetes.target[:-20]
diabetes_y_test = diabetes.target[-20:]
plt.scatter(diabetes_X_train, diabetes_y_train,  color='black')
plt.scatter(diabetes_X_test, diabetes_y_test,  color='red')
show(plt)

%md To keep things simple, we will ignore few important aspects in first few cells, such as regularization and intercept. ### Algorithm 1: Linear Regression - Direct Solve (no intercept, no regularization) #### Least squares formulation: w* = argminw ||Xw-y||2 = argminw (y - Xw)'(y - Xw) = argminw (w'(X'X)w - w'(X'y))/2 Setting the gradient, dw = (X'X)w - (X'y) to 0, w = (X'X)-1(X' y) = solve(X'X, X'y)

Least squares formulation:

Setting the gradient, dw = (X'X)w - (X'y) to 0, w = (X'X)-1(X' y) = solve(X'X, X'y)

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from systemml import MLContext, dml

algo = """
    A = t(X) %*% X
    b = t(X) %*% y
    w = solve(A, b)
"""
ml = MLContext(sc)
script = dml(algo).input(X=diabetes_X_train, y=diabetes_y_train).output('w')
out = ml.execute(script)
w = out.get('w').toNumPy()
plt.plot(diabetes_X_test, w*diabetes_X_test, color='blue', linestyle ='dotted')
show(plt)

%md

### Algorithm 2: Linear Regression - Batch Gradient Descent (no intercept, no regularization)

Step 1: Start with an initial point 
while(not converged) {
       Step 2: Compute gradient dw.
       Step 3: Compute stepsize alpha.
       Step 4: Update: w<sub>new</sub> = w<sub>old</sub> + alpha*dw
}

#### Gradient formula
dw = r = (X'X)w - (X'y)

#### Step size formula
Find number alpha  to minimize f(w + alpha*r)
alpha = -(r'r)/(r'X'Xr)

![Gradient Descent](http://blog.datumbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/gradient-descent.png)

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from systemml import MLContext, dml

algo = """
    max_iter = 1
    w = matrix(0, rows=ncol(X), cols=1)
    for(i in 1:max_iter){
        XtX = t(X) %*% X
        dw = XtX %*%w - t(X) %*% y
        alpha = -(t(dw) %*% dw) / (t(dw) %*% XtX %*% dw)
        w = w + dw*alpha
    }
"""
ml = MLContext(sc)
script = dml(algo).input(X=diabetes_X_train, y=diabetes_y_train).output('w')
out = ml.execute(script)
w = out.get('w').toNumPy()
plt.plot(diabetes_X_test, w*diabetes_X_test, color='red', linestyle ='dashed')
show(plt)

%md

### Algorithm 3: Linear Regression - Minibatch Gradient Descent  (no intercept, no regularization)

Learning rate, lr can decay exponentially or set to relatively small value.

Step 1: Start with an initial point 
while(not converged) {
       Step 2: Extract a batch from the entire dataset.
       Step 3: Compute gradient dw.
       Step 5: Update: w<sub>new</sub> = w<sub>old</sub> - lr*dw
}

Instead of computing gradient over the entire dataset, here we compute the gradient over a batch.

We will skip several [variants of gradient descent algorithms](http://sebastianruder.com/optimizing-gradient-descent/index.html), such as Nesterov's Accelerated Gradient, Momentum, AdaGrad, etc.

paragraphs.text:
%md

### Algorithm 4: Linear Regression - Conjugate Gradient (no intercept, no regularization)

Problem with gradient descent: Takes very similar directions many times

Solution: Enforce conjugacy

Step 1: Start with an initial point 
while(not converged) {
       Step 2: Compute gradient dw.
       Step 3: Compute stepsize alpha.
       Step 4: Compute next direction p by enforcing conjugacy with previous direction.
       Step 4: Update: w<sub>new</sub> = w<sub>old</sub> + alpha*p
}

![Gradient Descent vs Conjugate Gradient](http://i.stack.imgur.com/zh1HH.png)

result.msg:

Problem with gradient descent: Takes very similar directions many times

Solution: Enforce conjugacy

Step 1: Start with an initial point
while(not converged) {
    Step 2: Compute gradient dw.
    Step 3: Compute stepsize alpha.
    Step 4: Compute next direction p by enforcing conjugacy with previous direction.
    Step 4: Update: wnew = wold + alpha*p
}

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from systemml import MLContext, dml

algo = """
    # Linear Regression Conjugate Gradient (without intercept)
    m = ncol(X); i = 1; max_iter = 1;
    w = matrix (0, rows = m, cols = 1); # initialize weights to 0
    dw = - t(X) %*% y; p = - dw;        # dw = (X'X)w - (X'y)
    norm_r2 = sum (dw ^ 2); 
    for(i in 1:max_iter) {
        q = t(X) %*% (X %*% p)
    	alpha = norm_r2 / sum (p * q);  # Minimizes f(w - alpha*r)
    	w = w + alpha * p;              # update weights
    	dw = dw + alpha * q;           
    	old_norm_r2 = norm_r2; norm_r2 = sum (dw ^ 2);
    	p = -dw + (norm_r2 / old_norm_r2) * p; # next direction - conjugacy to previous direction
    	i = i + 1;
    }
"""
ml = MLContext(sc)
script = dml(algo).input(X=diabetes_X_train, y=diabetes_y_train).output('w')
out = ml.execute(script)
w = out.get('w').toNumPy()
plt.plot(diabetes_X_test, w*diabetes_X_test, color='violet', linestyle ='dotted')
show(plt)
